g.text: DeepRead: Document Structure-Aware Reasoning to Enhance Agentic Search
Artificial Intelligence as Strange Intelligence: Against Linear
Zhanli Li, Huiwen Tian, Lvzhou Luo, Yixuan Cao, Ping Luo
DeepRead: Document Structure-Aware Reasoning to Enhance Agentic
Zhanli Li, Huiwen Tian, Lvzhou Luo, Yixuan Cao, Ping Luo
With the rapid progress of tool-using and agentic large language models (LLMs), Retrieval-Augmented
Generation (RAG) is evolving from one-shot, passive retrieval into multi-turn, decision-driven
evidence acquisition. Despite strong results in open-domain settings, existing agentic search
frameworks commonly treat long documents as flat collections of chunks, underutilizing document-native
priors such as hierarchical organization and sequential discourse structure. We introduce DeepRead, a
MINT: Minimal Information Neuro-Symbolic Tree for
structure-aware, multi-turn document reasoning agent that explicitly operationalizes these priors for
Objective-Driven Knowledge-Gap Reasoning and Active Elicitation
long-document question answering. DeepRead leverages LLM-based OCR model to convert PDFs into
Zeyu Fang, Tian Lan, Mahdi Imani
structured Markdown that preserves headings and paragraph boundaries. It then indexes documents at the
paragraph level and assigns each paragraph a coordinate-style metadata key encoding its section
identity and in-section order. Building on this representation, DeepRead equips the LLM with two
complementary tools: a Retrieve tool that localizes relevant paragraphs while exposing their
structural coordinates (with lightweight scanning context), and a ReadSection tool that enables
Evaluating Large Language Models on Solved and Unsolved Problems
contiguous, order-preserving reading within a specified section and paragraph range. Our experiments
in Graph Theory: Implications for Computing Education
demonstrate that DeepRead achieves significant improvements over Search-o1-style agentic search in
Adithya Kulkarni and Mohna Chakraborty and Jay Bagga
document question answering. The synergistic effect between retrieval and reading tools is also
validated. Our fine-grained behavioral analysis reveals a reading and reasoning paradigm resembling
